{"title_page": "Guat\u00f3 language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n| name = Guat\u00f3\n| nativename = \n| states = [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]]\n| region = [[Mato Grosso do Sul]] state: [[Paraguay River]] banks and up [[S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River (Mato Grosso)|S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River]], along Bolivian border;<ref name=e19/> also [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)]]:  [[Uberaba Lake]]<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref>\n| familycolor = American\n| family = [[language isolate]]\n| ethnicity = 370 [[Guat\u00f3 people]] (2008)<ref name=e19/>\n| speakers = 5\n| date = 2011\n| ref = e19\n| iso3 = gta\n| glotto = guat1253\n| glottorefname = Guat\u00f3\n| map = Guato language.png\n| mapcaption = \n| notice = IPA\n}}\n\n'''Guat\u00f3''' is a possible [[language isolate]] spoken by 1% of the [[Guat\u00f3 people]] of Brazil. Kaufman (1990) provisionally classified it as a branch of the [[Macro-J\u00ea languages]], but no evidence for this was found by Eduardo Ribeiro.\n\nIn [[Mato Grosso do Sul]], Brazil, Guat\u00f3 is spoken on the banks of the [[Paraguay River]] and up the [[S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River (Mato Grosso)|S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River]], along the Bolivian border.<ref name=\"Ethnologue22-BR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/country/BR/languages |title=Brazil languages |work=[[Ethnologue]]: Languages of the World |edition=22nd |editor1-last=Eberhard |editor1-first=David M. |editor2-last=Simons |editor2-first=Gary F. |editor3-last=Fennig |editor3-first=Charles D. |date=2019 |location=Dallas |publisher=[[SIL International]]}}</ref> It is also spoken at [[Uberaba Lake]]<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref> in [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)]].\n\n==Phonology==\nThe Guat\u00f3 vowel system, like that of Macro-J\u00ea languages, collapses a three-way distinction of height in oral vowels to two in nasal vowels.<ref>A. P. Palacios, 1984; A. V. Postigo, 2009</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\" style=text-align:center\n! \n! colspan=\"3\" | Oral\n! colspan=\"3\" | [[nasal vowel|Nasal]]\n|-\n! \n! [[front vowel|Front]]\n! [[central vowel|Central]]\n! [[back vowel|Back]]\n! [[front vowel|Front]]\n! [[central vowel|Central]]\n! [[back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n! [[close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA|i}}  \n| {{IPA|\u0268}}\n| {{IPA|u}}\n| {{IPA|\u0129}}\n| {{IPA|\u0268\u0303}}\n| {{IPA|\u0169}} \n|-\n! [[mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPA|e}}  \n| \n| {{IPA|o}}\n| rowspan=2 | {{IPA|\u1ebd}}\n| colspan=2 rowspan=2 | {{IPA|\u00e3}} \n|-\n! [[open vowel|Open]]\n| {{IPA|\u025b}}  \n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|\u0254}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align:center\n! colspan=2 | \n! [[labial consonant|Labial]]\n! [[denti-alveolar consonant|Denti-<br>alveolar]]\n! [[postalveolar consonant|Post-<br>alveolar]]\n! [[velar consonant|Velar]]\n! [[labialized velar consonant|Labio-<br>velar]]\n! [[glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! colspan=2 | [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPA|m}}  \n| {{IPA|n}}\n| \n| \n|\n| \n|-\n! rowspan=2 | [[plosive consonant|Plosive]]\n! <small>[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| {{IPA|b}}  \n| {{IPA|d}}\n| {{IPA|d\u0292}}\n| {{IPA|\u0261}}\n| {{IPA|\u0261\u02b7}}\n| \n|-\n! <small>[[voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| {{IPA|p}}  \n| {{IPA|t}}\n| {{IPA|t\u0283}}\n| {{IPA|k}}\n| {{IPA|k\u02b7}} \n| \n|-\n! colspan=2 | [[fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n| {{IPA|f}}  \n| \n|\n|\n|\n| {{IPA|h}}\n|-\n! colspan=2 | [[Sonorant]]\n| {{IPA|w}}\n| {{IPA|\u027e}}\n| {{IPA|j}}\n|\n| \n| \n|}\n\n==Vocabulary==\n[[\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka|Loukotka]] (1968) lists the following basic vocabulary items for Guat\u00f3.<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref>\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! gloss !! Guat\u00f3\n|-\n| one || chen\u00e9he\n|-\n| two || d\u00fani\n|-\n| three || chum\u00f3\n|-\n| tooth || maku\u00e1\n|-\n| tongue || mundoku\u00edr\n|-\n| hand || mara\n|-\n| woman || muazya\n|-\n| water || m\u00e1g\u0169\n|-\n| fire || mat\u00e1\n|-\n| moon || m\u00fapina\n|-\n| maize || madzy\u00e9ro\n|-\n| jaguar || m\u00e9pago\n|-\n| house || mov\u00edr\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*Alain Fabre, 2005, ''Diccionario etnoling\u00fc\u00edstico y gu\u00eda bibliogr\u00e1fica de los pueblos ind\u00edgenas sudamericanos: GUAT\u00d3''.[http://www.ling.fi/Entradas%20diccionario/Dic=Guat%f3.pdf]\n\n{{Languages of Brazil}}\n{{language families}}\n{{South American languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guato language}}\n[[Category:Macro-J\u00ea languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of South America (Central)]]\n[[Category:Endangered indigenous languages of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Language isolates of South America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n| name = Guat\u00f3\n| nativename = \n| states = [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]]\n| region = [[Mato Grosso do Sul]] state: [[Paraguay River]] banks and up [[S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River (Mato Grosso)|S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River]], along Bolivian border;<ref name=e19/> also [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)]]:  [[Uberaba Lake]]<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref>\n| familycolor = American\n| family = [[language isolate]]\n| ethnicity = 370 [[Guat\u00f3 people]] (2008)<ref name=e19/>\n| speakers = 5\n| date = 2011\n| ref = e19\n| iso3 = gta\n| glotto = guat1253\n| glottorefname = Guat\u00f3\n| map = Guato language.png\n| mapcaption = \n| notice = IPA\n}}\n\n'''Guat\u00f3''' is a possible [[language isolate]] spoken by 1% of the [[Guat\u00f3 people]] of Brazil. Kaufman (1990) provisionally classified it as a branch of the [[Macro-J\u00ea languages]], but no evidence for this was found by Eduardo Ribeiro.\n\nIn [[Mato Grosso do Sul]], Brazil, it is spoken on the banks of the [[Paraguay River]] and up the [[S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River (Mato Grosso)|S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o River]], along the Bolivian border.<ref name=\"Ethnologue22-BR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/country/BR/languages |title=Brazil languages |work=[[Ethnologue]]: Languages of the World |edition=22nd |editor1-last=Eberhard |editor1-first=David M. |editor2-last=Simons |editor2-first=Gary F. |editor3-last=Fennig |editor3-first=Charles D. |date=2019 |location=Dallas |publisher=[[SIL International]]}}</ref> It is also spoken at [[Uberaba Lake]]<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref> in [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)]].\n\n==Phonology==\nThe Guato vowel system, like that of Macro-J\u00ea languages, collapses a three-way distinction of height in oral vowels to two in nasal vowels.<ref>A. P. Palacios, 1984; A. V. Postigo, 2009</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\" style=text-